0	\chapter{The Jacobian as an abelian variety}
1	\label{chap:Jacobian}
2	Let \(C\) be a smooth proper curve over \(k\) in the sense of Chapter~\ref{chap:Genus}, with genus \(g = g(C)\).
3	The Jacobian is built as the Albanese object of \(C\) in the category of smooth proper group schemes over \(k\), and the construction stratifies by genus. For positive genus the witness \emph{object} is the abelian variety \(\Pic^0_{C/k}\) produced by \textbf{Route~A (the Picard scheme via FGA representability)}: this is the project's committed critical path, and it is \emph{mandatory} for the positive-genus object regardless of any other route choice --- the object must be a genuine \(g\)-dimensional abelian variety even when \(C(k) = \emptyset\) (see \cref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness} Route~A and \cref{def:positiveGenusWitness}). The FGA representability for \(\Pic_{C/k}\) and its Hilbert/Quot prerequisites are the single largest Mathlib build-out the project gates on. For genus \(0\) the witness object is instead the trivial scheme \(\Spec k\), \textbf{decoupled} from Route~A's representability engine; the only remaining content in that arm is a rigidity \emph{statement}, the characteristic-free keystone \cref{prop:rigidity_genus0_curve_to_AV} developed in \cref{chap:AbelianVarietyRigidity} via the Milne \S I.3 rigidity chain (Rigidity Lemma \(+\) additivity Corollary~1.5 \(+\) Corollary~1.2 \(+\) rational-map extension), \emph{cube-free} and \emph{not} the differential / Serre-duality argument. The over-\(\bar k\) declaration \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} of \cref{chap:RigidityKbar}, which still carries \([\mathtt{CharZero}]\), is the retained fallback-(a) artifact and is \emph{not} the declaration the genus-\(0\) witness consumes.
4	\section{The Albanese construction}
5	For a smooth proper curve \(C\) over \(k\), the Albanese variety is the universal abelian variety receiving a morphism from \(C\). Over an algebraically closed field this is classically identified with the connected component of the identity of the Picard scheme, but we construct it directly from symmetric powers.
6	\subsection{Symmetric powers and the Abel--Jacobi map}
7	Let \(C^{(g)} = \Sym^g(C)\) be the \(g\)\textsuperscript{th} symmetric power of \(C\) (the quotient of \(C^g\) by the action of the symmetric group \(S_g\)). It is a smooth proper scheme over \(k\) of dimension \(g\). Fix a \(k\)-rational point \(P_0 \in C(k)\). The map
8	\[
9	  \sigma \colon C^{(g)} \longrightarrow \Pic^g_{C/k}, \qquad
10	  \sum_{i=1}^g [P_i] \longmapsto \mathcal O_C\bigl(\textstyle\sum_{i=1}^g P_i - g P_0\bigr)
11	\]
12	is surjective and birational onto its image; its fibres are projective spaces (Brill--Noether--Riemann--Roch). Choosing \(P_0\) gives a translation isomorphism \(\Pic^g_{C/k} \xrightarrow{\;\sim\;} \Pic^0_{C/k}\), and the Stein factorisation of \(\sigma\) yields the Jacobian as the connected component of the identity.
13	In the Lean formalisation we do not have general symmetric powers of schemes (or quotients by finite group actions) in Mathlib. We therefore take a more direct approach: we define the Jacobian as the Albanese object of \(C\) inside the category of smooth proper group schemes over \(k\), using the universal property and the known dimension formula.
14	\subsection{The Albanese universal property}
15	\begin{definition}\leanok
16	[Albanese universal property of a pointed curve]
17	  \label{def:IsAlbanese}
18	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.IsAlbanese}
19	  % SOURCE: [Kleiman, The Picard scheme], Remark rmk:Alb (the Albanese map), FGA Explained ch.~5; arXiv:math/0504020, p.~50  (read from references/kleiman-picard-src/kleiman-picard.tex)
20	  % SOURCE QUOTE: "Reversing the preceding argument, we see that every
21	  % such \(b\) arises from a unique map \(a\:B^*\to \IPic_{X/k}\) such that
22	  % \(a(0)=0\).  Since \(B^*\) is integral, \(a\) factors through \(P\).  Thus the
23	  % maps \(a\:B^*\to P\) and \(b\:X\to B\) are in bijective correspondence.
24	  % Plainly, this correspondence is compatible with maps \(b'\:B\to B'\) such
25	  % that \(b'(0)=0\).  In particular, \(1_P\) corresponds to a natural map
26	  % \(u\:X\to A\) such that \(u(x)=0\), and every map \(b\:X\to B\) factors
27	  % uniquely through \(u\)."
28	  \textit{Source: Kleiman, The Picard Scheme, Remark (the Albanese map, rmk:Alb).}
29	  Let \((C, P)\) be a smooth proper geometrically irreducible curve over \(k\) with a marked \(k\)-rational point \(P \in C(k)\). A smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme \(J\) over \(k\) is an \emph{Albanese object} for \((C, P)\) if there exists a morphism \(\iota \colon C \to J\) sending \(P\) to the identity element \(\eta \in J\), and such that every morphism \(f \colon C \to A\) from \(C\) to a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme \(A\) with \(f(P) = \eta_A\) factors uniquely as \(f = \iota \circ g\) for some morphism of group schemes \(g \colon J \to A\).
30	\end{definition}
31	\begin{remark}
32	  \label{rem:IsAlbanese_typeclasses}
33	  The Lean encoding of Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese} takes the four abelian-variety conditions on \(J\) --- group-object structure, properness, smoothness, geometric irreducibility --- as \emph{typeclass parameters} of the declaration \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.IsAlbanese}, not as conjuncts inside the body. The body is the existential statement on \(\iota\) and its universal-factorisation property; the four hypotheses on \(J\) sit on the binder of the definition. A downstream user constructs an \texttt{IsAlbanese} term against these instances and threads them at every use site (cf.\ the \texttt{letI} chain in \texttt{AbelJacobi.ofCurve} which installs all four instances on \(\Jac(C)\) before applying any Albanese consequence). The same convention is used for the target abelian variety \(A\) in the universal-property clause.
34	\end{remark}
35	\subsection{Extracting the universal morphism}
36	An \texttt{IsAlbanese} term \(h\) packages, behind a single existential, the universal pointed morphism \(\iota \colon C \to J\) together with its two characterising properties: the pointed condition \(P \circ \iota = \eta_J\) and the universal-factorisation property of \(\iota\). The data and the two properties are extracted from the existential body by the following trio of helpers, each implemented in Lean via \texttt{Classical.choose} / \texttt{Classical.choose\_spec} on the existential content of \texttt{IsAlbanese}.
37	\begin{definition}
38	\leanok
39	[The Albanese universal morphism]
40	  \label{def:IsAlbanese_ofCurve}
41	  
42	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.IsAlbanese.ofCurve}
43	  Given a pointed curve \((C, P)\) and an Albanese term \(h \colon \mathrm{IsAlbanese}\,C\,P\,J\), the \emph{universal morphism} of \(h\) is the morphism
44	  \[
45	    \iota := h.\mathtt{ofCurve} \colon C \to J,
46	  \]
47	  obtained by \texttt{Classical.choose} on the existential body of \(h\).
48	\end{definition}
49	\begin{lemma}
50	\leanok
51	[Pointed condition for the universal morphism]
52	  \label{lem:IsAlbanese_comp_ofCurve}
53	  
54	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.IsAlbanese.comp_ofCurve}
55	  The universal morphism \(h.\mathtt{ofCurve}\) sends the marked point \(P\) to the identity of \(J\):
56	  \[
57	    P \circ h.\mathtt{ofCurve} \;=\; \eta_J.
58	  \]
59	\end{lemma}

0	\chapter{Rigidity for morphisms of schemes (scheme-level form; Mumford \S4 in the abelian-variety case)}
1	\label{chap:Rigidity}
2	
3	This chapter records a self-contained helper: \emph{rigidity for morphisms of schemes that agree on a non-empty open}. The classical motivation is Mumford's rigidity for abelian-variety morphisms, but the project's formalised statement is more general: the source-side group-object hypothesis is unused by the proof and is dropped.
4	
5	The lemma is independent of the construction of \(\Jac(C)\). It is the load-bearing input for the M2.a sub-step of the genus-0 Albanese-witness argument (Jacobian.tex \S C.2.b), where the source is taken to be \(\mathbb P^1_{\bar k}\) (which is \emph{not} a group scheme).
6	
7	\section{Statement}
8	
9	\begin{theorem}\leanok
10	[Rigidity for morphisms of schemes (scheme-level form)]
11	  \label{thm:GrpObj_eq_of_eqOnOpen}
12	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Over.ext_of_eqOnOpen}
13	  Let \(k\) be a field. Let \(X\) be a reduced geometrically irreducible \(k\)-scheme and let \(Y\) be a separated \(k\)-scheme. Let \(g_1, g_2 \colon X \to Y\) be two morphisms of \(k\)-schemes, and let \(U \subseteq X\) be a non-empty open subset. If
14	  \[
15	    U.\iota \circ g_1 \;=\; U.\iota \circ g_2
16	  \]
17	  as scheme morphisms (where \(U.\iota \colon U \hookrightarrow X\) is the canonical open immersion), then \(g_1 = g_2\) as morphisms of \(k\)-schemes.
18	\end{theorem}
19	
20	\begin{remark}
21	  The classical Mumford rigidity theorem (\emph{Abelian Varieties}, \S4) usually states the special case where \(Y\) is an abelian variety and the conclusion is phrased as ``a morphism vanishing on a non-empty open is zero''. The two forms are interderivable in the abelian-variety case via the difference morphism \(\delta = g_1 \cdot g_2^{-1}\) formed from the group law on \(Y\). The project formalises the more general statement above because the M2.a (genus-0 Albanese-witness) consumer specifically needs the source to be \(\mathbb P^1_{\bar k}\), which is not a group scheme: the abelian-variety packaging is consumer-side and the scheme-level statement is what the proof actually establishes.
22	
23	  The refactor that landed the scheme-level form (iter-125; see \texttt{analogies/rigidity-refactor.md}) dropped 8 unused hypotheses from the project's original group-scheme-flavoured declaration and weakened the target-side \([\mathtt{IsProper}\ Y.\mathrm{hom}]\) to \([\mathtt{IsSeparated}\ Y.\mathrm{hom}]\).
24	\end{remark}
25	
26	\section{Proof sketch}
27	
28	\begin{proof}
29	  \leanok
30	  We reduce to Mathlib's \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.ext\_of\_isDominant\_of\_isSeparated'} (\texttt{Mathlib.AlgebraicGeometry.Morphisms.Separated}), which gives the standard scheme-level fact that two morphisms from a reduced scheme to a separated scheme agreeing on a dominant subscheme agree everywhere.
31	
32	  The three load-bearing instances feeding that closure are:
33	  \begin{itemize}
34	    \item \emph{\(Y \to \Spec k\) is separated.} Hypothesis \([\mathtt{IsSeparated}\ Y.\mathrm{hom}]\) provides this directly (no projection from \(\mathtt{IsProper}\) needed). The \texttt{OverClass.fromOver} instance transports it to the form \(\mathtt{IsSeparated}\ (Y.\mathrm{left} \downarrow \Spec k)\) that the closure step expects.
35	    \item \emph{\(X\) is an irreducible space.} Hypothesis \([\mathtt{GeometricallyIrreducible}\ X.\mathrm{hom}]\) over the field-spectrum base \(\Spec k\) (which is a single point, hence subsingleton) yields \(\mathtt{IrreducibleSpace}\ X.\mathrm{left}\) via \texttt{GeometricallyIrreducible.irreducibleSpace\_of\_subsingleton}.
36	    \item \emph{The inclusion \(U.\iota\) is dominant.} A non-empty open in an irreducible space is dense, and a dense open immersion is dominant: \texttt{Scheme.PartialMap.Opens.isDominant\_ι}.
37	  \end{itemize}
38	  With these three derived instances and the hypothesis \([\mathtt{IsReduced}\ X.\mathrm{left}]\), the closure \texttt{ext\_of\_isDominant\_of\_isSeparated'} produces the underlying scheme-morphism equality \(g_1.\mathrm{left} = g_2.\mathrm{left}\) from the agreement-on-\(U\) hypothesis. The promotion to \(g_1 = g_2\) in \(\mathrm{Over}\ (\Spec k)\) uses \texttt{Over.OverMorphism.ext}.
39	
40	  \medskip
41	  \noindent\textbf{Mathlib ingredients.}
42	  \begin{itemize}
43	    \item \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.ext\_of\_isDominant\_of\_isSeparated'} for the scheme-level closure step.
44	    \item \texttt{GeometricallyIrreducible.irreducibleSpace\_of\_subsingleton} to derive irreducibility of \(X.\mathrm{left}\).
45	    \item \texttt{Scheme.PartialMap.Opens.isDominant\_ι} to derive dominance of the open immersion \(U.\iota\) from the non-empty hypothesis.
46	    \item \texttt{Over.OverMorphism.ext} to promote underlying scheme equality to \(\mathrm{Over}\)-morphism equality.
47	    \item No abelian-variety / group-object infrastructure is needed: smoothness, properness, and group-object hypotheses on \(X\) and \(Y\) are all dropped from the formalised statement.
48	  \end{itemize}
49	\end{proof}

0	\chapter{The Abel--Jacobi map}
1	\label{chap:AbelJacobi}
2	Let \(C\) be a smooth proper curve over \(k\) as in Chapter~\ref{chap:Genus}, and let \(\Jac(C)\) be its Jacobian (Definition~\ref{def:Jacobian}). The constructions of this chapter consume only the Albanese universal property of \(\Jac(C)\), as packaged by Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese} and provided uniformly in the marked point by Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}. The Lean formalisation closes every block in this chapter by a single projection from the Albanese structure \(\mathrm{IsAlbanese}\,C\,P\,\Jac(C)\); the corresponding classical line-bundle / Pic-scheme description is recorded as a remark for each block.
3	\section{Definition}
4	\begin{definition}\leanok
5	[Abel--Jacobi map]
6	  \label{def:ofCurve}
7	  \uses{def:Jacobian, def:IsAlbanese, thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}
8	  
9	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.ofCurve}
10	  Let \(P \colon \Spec k \to C\) be a \(k\)-rational point of \(C\), equivalently a morphism \(P \colon \mathbf 1 \to C\) in the category of \(k\)-schemes over \(\Spec k\). By Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness} the Jacobian \(\Jac(C)\) of Definition~\ref{def:Jacobian} carries, for each such marked point \(P\), an Albanese structure \(\mathrm{IsAlbanese}\,C\,P\,\Jac(C)\) in the sense of Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}. The \emph{Abel--Jacobi map at \(P\)} is the universal pointed morphism \(\iota_P\) supplied by that Albanese structure:
11	  \[
12	    \alpha_P \;:=\; \iota_P \;\colon\; C \;\longrightarrow\; \Jac(C).
13	  \]
14	  Equivalently, \(\alpha_P\) is the projection of the universal-pointed-morphism field of the Albanese predicate \(\mathrm{IsAlbanese}\,C\,P\,\Jac(C)\), evaluated at the marked point \(P\).
15	\end{definition}
16	\begin{remark}
17	[Classical description (Pic-scheme route)]
18	  \label{rem:ofCurve_classical}
19	  Classically (cf.\ Hartshorne~III.4 and FGA Explained, Chapter~9), the Abel--Jacobi map at \(P\) admits the line-bundle description
20	  \[
21	    \alpha_P \colon C \;\longrightarrow\; \Pic^0_{C/k},\qquad Q \;\longmapsto\; [\mathcal O_C(Q - P)].
22	  \]
23	  Functorially, it is the morphism in the category of \(k\)-schemes induced by the line bundle \(\mathcal O_{C \times C}(\Delta - p_1^* P)\) on \(C \times C\) via the universal property of \(\Pic^0_{C/k}\) as the moduli space of degree-\(0\) line bundles on \(C\). The Lean formalisation does not follow this route: the Pic-scheme representability machinery (Route~A of the proof of Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}, in particular sub-step~A.2) is not currently available in Mathlib. See Layer~I of Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian} for the formalisation route actually taken.
24	\end{remark}
25	\section{Pointed property}
26	\begin{lemma}\leanok
27	[\(\alpha_P\) sends \(P\) to \(0\)]
28	  \uses{def:ofCurve, thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}
29	  \label{lem:comp_ofCurve}
30	  
31	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Jacobian.comp_ofCurve}
32	  \(P \;\circ\; \alpha_P \;=\; \eta[\Jac(C)]\), where \(\eta[\Jac(C)]\) is the identity element of the group scheme \(\Jac(C)\).
33	\end{lemma}
34	\begin{proof}
35	  \leanok
36	  The Lean closure is the field projection from the Albanese structure \(\mathrm{IsAlbanese}\,C\,P\,\Jac(C)\) supplied by Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}. By Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}, this predicate carries among its data the assertion \(P \circ \iota_P = \eta_{\Jac(C)}\) that the universal pointed morphism sends the marked point to the identity of the target group scheme. Since \(\alpha_P := \iota_P\) by Definition~\ref{def:ofCurve}, the claim is precisely the pointed-property field of that Albanese structure.
37	\end{proof}
38	\begin{remark}
39	[Classical description]
40	  \label{rem:comp_ofCurve_classical}
